 {"id":"bd-10i.4","title":"Phase 2: Diff + Presenter (Near-minimal ANSI)","description":"# Phase 2: Diff + Presenter (Near-minimal ANSI)

## Purpose
Implement the diff engine and ANSI presenter that transform buffer changes into minimal terminal output. This is where the 'zero-flicker' promise is delivered.

## Components

### BufferDiff
- Compute diff between old and new buffers
- Row-major scan for cache efficiency
- Output as list of changed positions
- Convert to ChangeRuns for efficient emission

### ChangeRun
- Contiguous run of changed cells on a single row
- Allows single cursor move per run instead of per-cell

### Presenter (State-Tracked ANSI Writer)
- Tracks current style, link, cursor position
- Only emits changes from tracked state
- Uses BufWriter with 64KB buffer
- Supports synchronized output (DEC mode 2026)

## Key Decisions (from ADRs)

### Style Emission Strategy
- v1 default: Reset+apply (SGR 0 then re-apply)
- Simple and correct, though more bytes
- Incremental/hybrid behind feature flag until benchmarks justify

### Synchronized Output
- Use CSI ? 2026 h/l when available
- Reduces flicker by batching updates
- Must work without it (graceful degradation)

### Run Grouping
- Emit changes in row-major runs
- Single cursor move per run
- Sequential character emission within runs (cursor advances naturally)

## Exit Criteria
- Single buffered write per frame achieved
- Run grouping works correctly
- Style state cannot leak across runs (terminal-model tests)
- Links (OSC 8) cannot remain open after present/exit

## Success Criteria
- [ ] BufferDiff is correct and fast (row-major; scratch reuse; property tests where possible).
